WEBVTT

00:00.610 --> 00:10.381
And now as we move from the gathering portion of our service to the listening, our scripture reading today is from the book of Romans chapter 10, verses nine through 17.

00:12.664 --> 00:20.573
If you declare with your mouth, Jesus is Lord and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.

00:21.714 --> 00:28.882
For it is with your heart that you believe and are justified and it is with your mouth that you profess your faith and are saved.

00:29.922 --> 00:37.031
As Scripture says, anyone who believes in Him will never be put to shame, for there is no difference between Jew and Gentile.

00:37.832 --> 00:42.478
The same Lord is Lord of all, and richly blesses all who call on Him.

00:43.539 --> 00:46.923
For everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved.

00:48.405 --> 00:51.349
How then can they call on the one they have not believed in?

00:52.410 --> 00:55.014
And how can they believe in the one whom they have not heard?

00:55.995 --> 00:58.418
And how can they hear without someone preaching to them?

00:59.330 --> 01:02.074
and how can anyone preach unless they are sent?

01:03.176 --> 01:08.103
As it is written, how beautiful are to feed of those who bring good news.

01:09.866 --> 01:12.109
But not all the Israelites accepted the good news.

01:12.971 --> 01:24.748
For Isaiah says, Lord, who has believed our message, consequently, faith comes from hearing, from hearing the message, and the message is heard through the Word about Christ.

01:25.610 --> 01:26.751
This is the Word of the Lord.

01:27.572 --> 01:28.594
Thanks be to God.

01:28.962 --> 01:32.406
So Pete, I guess you better get those beautiful feet up here and bring the good news.

01:35.389 --> 01:36.050
Thanks Gary.

01:36.731 --> 01:37.312
Morning church.

01:38.493 --> 01:39.875
Good to see you all today.

01:39.915 --> 01:41.637
My name's Pete and I want to welcome you.

01:42.197 --> 01:53.170
Whether you're a long time follower of Jesus or you're brand new to the Christian faith, whether you're maybe deconstructing some of your beliefs or

01:53.250 --> 01:54.392
healing from church hurt.

01:54.432 --> 02:01.401
Whether you're here for the first time or the last time, we're glad that you're here and it's good to be together today.

02:01.441 --> 02:08.351
We are in week eight of our 10 week series entitled, The Whole Gospel, both in faith and in either or world.

02:09.332 --> 02:19.186
And the idea is basically that if we as the church are gonna be faithful to the way of Jesus, then we aren't gonna fit nicely into any of the categories the world would put us in.

02:19.554 --> 02:23.561
Because true Christianity is neither conservative nor liberal.

02:24.142 --> 02:25.986
It's something else entirely.

02:26.026 --> 02:30.494
And that doesn't mean that we're always moderate or centrist either.

02:30.735 --> 02:39.090
It means that we inhabit this world as pilgrims and strangers whose first allegiance is to Christ in his kingdom.

02:39.650 --> 02:45.376
And so if you've been with us, we've been wading into some pretty heavy conversations over the last few weeks.

02:45.957 --> 02:49.201
Last week, we talked about the war in Israel and Palestine.

02:50.062 --> 02:53.145
The week before that, we talked about systemic racism.

02:54.046 --> 02:59.132
And this week, we're gonna talk about something even more controversial, evangelism.

02:59.652 --> 03:02.255
So it'll be fun, I promise.

03:04.157 --> 03:06.700
Let's start in verse 15 of Romans 10.

03:07.361 --> 03:08.242
Paul asks,

03:09.698 --> 03:13.284
How can anyone preach unless they are sent?

03:15.148 --> 03:19.876
In the original Greek, the word sent is missio, where we get the word mission.

03:20.637 --> 03:24.043
So to be sent is to be given a mission.

03:24.664 --> 03:34.802
And this is something that Christians have always recognized, that part of what it means to be followers of Jesus is that we are those who are sent by Him.

03:35.138 --> 03:41.568
All Christians believe that God has a mission in the world and he has called his people to be part of that mission.

03:42.850 --> 03:47.657
Where we might start to diverge is when we ask, what is that mission?

03:48.479 --> 03:50.602
And that's really our question for this morning.

03:50.963 --> 03:55.730
What is God's mission in the world and what does it look like for the church to live

03:55.842 --> 03:58.366
on that mission as those who are sent by Jesus.

03:58.967 --> 04:08.643
And so if we plug that question into the chart we've been using through this series, then you'll see kind of how the two main streams of Protestant Christianity have tended to answer these questions.

04:09.524 --> 04:10.907
Okay, so we'll walk through them real quickly.

04:10.987 --> 04:22.866
On the left in mainline Protestantism, the mission of the church is primarily about embodying the love of Jesus by working for social justice, which is all about alleviating human suffering

04:22.978 --> 04:33.814
by caring for people's physical needs in the name of Jesus, with the goal of seeing liberation for the poor and the oppressed so that they can flourish and thrive.

04:34.415 --> 04:39.883
And this is really the mission that Dr. King preached and practiced and ultimately gave his life for.

04:39.923 --> 04:46.994
On the right side of the chart in Evangelicalism, the church's primary mission is Evangelism.

04:47.330 --> 04:56.747
which just means sharing the gospel with as many people as possible, introducing them to Jesus, the one who can forgive their sins and meet their deepest spiritual needs.

04:57.549 --> 05:03.018
The goal in evangelism is conversion to see people repent and believe the good news.

05:03.499 --> 05:11.634
And this is the ministry that Reverend Billy Graham dedicated his life to, preaching the gospel and leading millions around the world to Christ.

05:12.514 --> 05:23.508
And so obviously this is a generalization, but these tend to be the two ends of the spectrum when it comes to how different streams of Christianity think about the mission of the church.

05:24.129 --> 05:29.275
So one side is all about social justice, the other side is all about evangelism.

05:29.856 --> 05:36.084
And I'm guessing that most churches you've been part of have tended to lean pretty hard one way or the other.

05:36.965 --> 05:41.010
Now at this point in the series, you already know what I'm gonna say next, don't you?

05:41.282 --> 05:42.324
Which side is better?

05:42.844 --> 05:46.350
Should we be about justice or should we be about evangelism?

05:47.852 --> 05:48.113
Both.

05:48.834 --> 05:50.597
For us, this isn't an either-or.

05:50.897 --> 05:52.600
This is a both-and.

05:53.121 --> 05:54.403
And this is what that looks like.

05:54.443 --> 05:59.951
We want to be a church that's committed to both social justice and evangelism.

05:59.971 --> 06:01.714
That's concerned about sin

06:01.794 --> 06:13.648
and suffering that cares about people's needs, both physical and spiritual, that celebrates liberation and conversion and that carries on the legacies of both Dr. King and Reverend Graham.

06:14.228 --> 06:19.254
And so that's our vision of what it looks like to live on mission for the whole gospel.

06:19.715 --> 06:27.784
We wanna practice the love of Jesus in works of justice and we wanna proclaim the love of Jesus in words of truth.

06:28.425 --> 06:29.266
It's both and.

06:29.442 --> 06:40.963
Now, the trick is that not only do we live in an either or world, but for most of us, we have one dominant hand and one non-dominant hand, right?

06:41.724 --> 06:46.573
And we tend to lean one way or another when it comes to mission.

06:47.775 --> 06:53.746
But if our goal is to be ambidextrous in our approach to the mission of God, then that's going to take some work.

06:54.274 --> 07:00.366
Starting with the fact that both of these terms, social justice and evangelism bring some pretty heavy baggage with them.

07:01.268 --> 07:03.132
So let's start with social justice.

07:04.114 --> 07:12.050
Most people aren't too offended by the word justice, but as soon as you add the word social in front of it, it tends to get somewhat controversial.

07:12.322 --> 07:20.652
and people who promote social justice often end up getting labeled as woke, or liberal, or SJW, social justice warriors.

07:21.473 --> 07:34.109
And if you've paid attention over the past few years, you know that lots has been said and written by Christians who want to explain the difference between biblical justice and social justice.

07:34.129 --> 07:39.295
But if you understand what these terms actually mean, then you know that they aren't pitted against one another.

07:39.795 --> 07:41.938
One is just the subset of the other.

07:42.434 --> 07:51.547
So in a biblical worldview, the way we talk about around here is that truth and justice are the two lenses through which we see the world.

07:52.348 --> 07:57.636
So when we talk about truth, we're talking about the way things are in reality.

07:58.177 --> 08:03.144
And when we talk about justice, we're talking about the way things are supposed to be.

08:04.045 --> 08:10.034
So justice truth corresponds to what is, justice corresponds to what ought to be.

08:10.466 --> 08:12.849
That's the idea of justice.

08:12.869 --> 08:17.014
And then under the heading of justice, there are all kinds of subsets.

08:17.555 --> 08:24.363
So criminal justice, for example, is about making things the way they're supposed to be when it comes to crime.

08:24.404 --> 08:29.910
Economic justice is about making things the way they're supposed to be in the economy.

08:30.772 --> 08:35.297
Environmental justice is about the way things are supposed to be in the environment.

08:35.497 --> 08:39.122
So social justice, then, is just about

08:39.330 --> 08:46.422
working to make things the way they're supposed to be in society as it relates to humans.

08:47.563 --> 08:56.358
So to say that you care about social justice is simply to say that you care about fixing what's broken within our society.

08:57.420 --> 09:06.194
And to work for social justice is to work for a world that looks less like the way it is and more like the way that it should be.

09:06.722 --> 09:12.068
or as Cornell with puts it, justice is what love looks like in public.

09:14.030 --> 09:20.516
So I'm always surprised when I hear people say that they don't agree or don't believe in social justice.

09:21.577 --> 09:25.922
To say you disagree with social justice is to say you prefer social injustice.

09:26.903 --> 09:33.810
To say that you want the world to remain in its current broken state rather than be restored to something better.

09:34.274 --> 09:39.463
So you're free to fight for social injustice if you'd like, but you should at least know what you're talking about.

09:39.503 --> 09:45.593
So the real question then isn't whether or not we want justice in society.

09:46.835 --> 09:50.481
The real question is where does our vision of justice come from?

09:51.723 --> 09:54.287
What constitutes a just society?

09:54.728 --> 09:58.514
Or who gets to decide how things ought to be?

09:59.490 --> 10:03.456
Those are tricky questions, and there's all kinds of ways people try to answer them.

10:03.837 --> 10:10.808
But for us, as followers of Jesus, our vision of justice is formed by our faith in Christ.

10:11.989 --> 10:20.623
And when Jesus imagines a world where everything is the way it's supposed to be, he calls that the kingdom of God.

10:22.205 --> 10:24.849
And so that's how the Bible defines justice.

10:25.630 --> 10:27.954
When things are on Earth,

10:28.258 --> 10:29.500
as they are in heaven.

10:30.341 --> 10:35.007
So that's what we mean by social justice, just justice in the realm of society.

10:35.447 --> 10:37.790
And that's why it's one of our core commitments as a church.

10:38.491 --> 10:44.038
We believe that justice is integral to the character of God and to the mission of God's people.

10:44.098 --> 10:48.123
And so we're gonna talk about justice a lot we always have and we always will.

10:49.184 --> 10:52.789
But it's only one half of our mission.

10:54.411 --> 10:56.754
The other side is this thing called evangelism.

10:57.794 --> 11:00.458
And that's not something we talk about as much around here.

11:00.699 --> 11:07.470
And I think it's safe to say that evangelism is probably our non-dominant hand here at Antioch.

11:07.490 --> 11:10.495
Have you ever tried to throw a football with your non-dominant hand?

11:11.036 --> 11:11.677
It's not great.

11:12.939 --> 11:16.425
And that's OK, but it means we have some work to do.

11:17.346 --> 11:22.194
And what's funny is that I've spent years trying to get evangelicals to care about social justice.

11:22.338 --> 11:26.448
My job this morning is to try to get a bunch of justice folks to care about evangelism.

11:26.488 --> 11:29.255
So that's what we're going to do for the rest of our time.

11:30.057 --> 11:31.661
We'll start by defining evangelism.

11:31.701 --> 11:36.152
It comes from the Greek word evangel, which simply means gospel or good news.

11:36.713 --> 11:40.242
So evangelism is announcing good news.

11:40.610 --> 11:48.281
Before it was ever a spiritual or religious term, it was essentially a term used in ancient forms of journalism.

11:48.661 --> 12:01.359
When something big happened that the people needed to know about and evangel, then there were messengers or evangelists whose job it was to go and tell everyone the good news that the war is over.

12:01.659 --> 12:02.280
You're safe.

12:02.400 --> 12:03.922
You can come out from hiding.

12:04.546 --> 12:17.639
Okay, so ever since the time of Christ, Christians have recognized that at the center of our faith is also an evangel, an announcement of good news that needs to be shared with the world.

12:18.379 --> 12:24.445
And so when we talk about evangelism as Christians, we're just talking about preaching the gospel of Jesus.

12:24.766 --> 12:26.948
We're talking about sharing our faith.

12:27.028 --> 12:33.554
We're talking about telling others about the hope that we've found for ourselves and for the world in Christ.

12:34.978 --> 12:43.789
Now the problem is, of course, that for many of us, evangelism, for whatever reason, doesn't sound like very good news to us.

12:44.850 --> 12:46.853
And there's a few different reasons for that.

12:47.394 --> 12:55.584
A few years ago, the Barnagroup put out a report on what Christian millennials believe about evangelism.

12:55.924 --> 12:57.847
I'm curious how many millennials are in the room.

12:57.887 --> 13:03.634
Raise your hand if you're born between roughly 1980 and 2000, okay?

13:03.906 --> 13:08.875
So basically, if you can relate to this meme, you're one of us.

13:10.317 --> 13:11.359
This may surprise you.

13:11.419 --> 13:15.687
I'm actually a millennial.

13:16.668 --> 13:22.018
I know I'm not what you picture with the dad bod and the grating beard and all that, but I was born in 1980.

13:22.439 --> 13:29.010
So technically, that makes me one of the world's oldest and wisest millennials.

13:29.922 --> 13:31.324
So these are my people.

13:31.504 --> 13:42.802
If we look at these statements from the Barnus study and the percentage of millennial Christians that agree with them, then you'll see what I mean about us having a complicated relationship with evangelism.

13:42.862 --> 13:44.124
So here's the three statements.

13:44.625 --> 13:50.194
The first is, part of my faith means being a witness about Jesus.

13:51.235 --> 13:52.978
And 96%

13:53.154 --> 13:53.975
say they agree.

13:54.516 --> 14:01.806
So pretty much all Christian millennials believe that part of what it means for us to follow Jesus is that we'll share our faith with others.

14:02.527 --> 14:03.408
Pretty straightforward.

14:04.329 --> 14:09.636
The next statement, the best thing that could ever happen to someone is for them to come to know Jesus.

14:10.177 --> 14:12.139
And 94% say they agree.

14:12.700 --> 14:17.486
Basically Jesus has changed my life and I want him to change the lives of my friends and neighbors too.

14:18.107 --> 14:20.571
And so, so far we're pretty much all on the same page.

14:21.412 --> 14:23.154
But then here's statement number three.

14:24.066 --> 14:31.597
It's wrong to share one's personal beliefs with someone of a different faith in hopes that they will one day share the same faith.

14:32.438 --> 14:36.003
And 47% say they agree with that statement.

14:36.864 --> 14:45.237
So basically half of Christian millennials think that sharing your faith with someone in hopes that they will come to faith is wrong.

14:45.297 --> 14:51.826
Not just awkward, not just optional, but actually immoral.

14:52.898 --> 14:54.920
Okay, so let me just recap the report.

14:55.661 --> 15:08.113
We want to tell people about Jesus and we hope that they'll come to know Jesus, but we think it's wrong to tell people about Jesus if we hope they come to know Jesus, right?

15:08.874 --> 15:10.195
Millennials are complicated.

15:10.556 --> 15:12.458
It's hard to be one of us.

15:15.621 --> 15:16.742
So how do we make sense of this?

15:17.222 --> 15:18.444
I've got a couple of theories.

15:19.164 --> 15:20.786
My first theory is that

15:20.866 --> 15:33.460
I think we're comfortable sharing our faith and talking about Jesus with people who are searching for meaning, who are looking for truth, who are asking us questions about what we believe.

15:33.540 --> 15:37.284
We're happy to tell them about the difference Jesus has made in our lives.

15:38.025 --> 15:49.458
But if somebody already has a religion or a set of beliefs that seems to be working for them, then we feel like it's wrong for us to try to impose our beliefs on them.

15:50.082 --> 15:52.286
So I think that could explain the disparity.

15:53.028 --> 15:56.214
But my other theory has to do with motivation.

15:57.216 --> 16:05.772
And it seems like they're saying that if your motivation for sharing your faith in Jesus is to convert someone, then that's a problem.

16:07.075 --> 16:12.946
Because it feels like you're treating them like a project rather than a person.

16:13.218 --> 16:22.289
It feels like the only reason you're interested in them and investing in them is so that you can convert them, which feels gross to us.

16:23.030 --> 16:26.394
It feels like we're selling Jesus and we don't like that.

16:27.316 --> 16:32.382
So I wanna press into that for just a moment and talk about our motivation for evangelism.

16:33.003 --> 16:38.109
How do we share our faith with others without reducing people into projects?

16:40.292 --> 16:42.194
And I would argue it's actually pretty simple.

16:43.394 --> 16:48.341
We do it by remembering that evangelism isn't actually our end goal.

16:49.362 --> 16:50.904
It's just a means to the end.

16:52.106 --> 16:52.947
What's the end goal?

16:54.749 --> 16:55.951
It's loving our neighbors.

16:57.954 --> 17:01.879
We don't love people in order to share the gospel with them.

17:02.900 --> 17:06.285
We share the gospel in order to love people.

17:08.828 --> 17:10.971
Our motivation is love.

17:12.353 --> 17:12.914
Think about it.

17:13.698 --> 17:19.086
If you have the best news in the world, why would you want to withhold that from your friends?

17:20.549 --> 17:27.039
Why wouldn't you want to tell the people around you that you found the greatest hope in the world?

17:28.381 --> 17:30.604
And we love doing this with other areas of life.

17:30.765 --> 17:34.971
We love telling people about a new restaurant we found or a new show that we're watching.

17:35.592 --> 17:42.002
We're all evangelists when it comes to our favorite podcasts or clothing brands or whatever it is.

17:43.010 --> 17:47.137
Why is it so different when it comes to the most important things in life?

17:49.040 --> 17:59.938
I'm not totally sure, but I do know that if you really want to love your neighbors, then what better way is there than by telling them the best news they could ever hear?

18:01.099 --> 18:02.301
The goal isn't conversion.

18:03.543 --> 18:04.024
It's love.

18:05.346 --> 18:10.034
Evangelism isn't about winning an argument or defending your faith.

18:11.010 --> 18:13.575
It's about loving your neighbor as you love yourself.

18:15.318 --> 18:18.985
So I understand why my fellow millennial struggle with evangelism.

18:19.045 --> 18:19.687
I really do.

18:20.608 --> 18:23.133
But for me personally, I just can't get rid of it.

18:24.376 --> 18:30.327
Because sharing the gospel is part of following Jesus and it always has been.

18:30.367 --> 18:34.034
Jesus himself was an evangelist.

18:34.658 --> 18:40.265
Everywhere he went, he was announcing the good news of God's kingdom to anyone who would listen.

18:40.725 --> 18:45.911
And he specifically calls his followers to live as he lived and do what he did.

18:47.373 --> 18:53.521
One of the most straightforward places is right after his resurrection, Jesus appears to his apostles in Mark 16.

18:54.582 --> 19:01.490
He said to them, go into all the world and preach the gospel to all creation.

19:03.938 --> 19:11.247
So sharing the gospel with the people around us has always been part of what it means to follow Jesus.

19:12.348 --> 19:15.252
And as I've told you before, you don't have to follow Jesus.

19:16.634 --> 19:17.154
You really don't.

19:18.376 --> 19:22.661
But if you're gonna follow Jesus, then you need to follow Him in this too.

19:26.626 --> 19:33.394
Now some of us are really gonna struggle with this because evangelism sounds

19:33.474 --> 19:42.051
hard or complicated or scary or just simply something we don't have time or bandwidth for in our lives right now.

19:44.155 --> 19:51.229
But the good news is that when you get the gospel, you realize that evangelism isn't actually something we have to do.

19:51.249 --> 19:53.554
It's something we get to do.

19:54.146 --> 19:56.689
And that's part of what Paul is saying in Romans 10.

19:57.149 --> 20:00.293
We're dropping in in the middle of a much larger conversation here.

20:00.693 --> 20:06.639
But in this letter to the church in Rome, Paul makes the case that sharing the gospel isn't something we do for God.

20:07.180 --> 20:09.282
It's a gift that God gives us.

20:10.223 --> 20:16.970
We get to be part of God's redeeming, reconciling, saving work in the world.

20:18.292 --> 20:20.594
So here's how Paul puts it, starting in verse 13.

20:21.570 --> 20:24.415
He says, everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved.

20:25.396 --> 20:28.902
How then can they call on the one they have not believed in?

20:28.942 --> 20:32.447
And how can they believe in the one of whom they have not heard?

20:33.149 --> 20:36.033
And how can they hear without someone preaching to them?

20:36.694 --> 20:40.200
And how can anyone preach unless they are sent?

20:42.203 --> 20:49.074
So Paul just asks a series of rhetorical questions to show that it's because of God's grace and kindness

20:49.442 --> 20:56.609
that the way he's chosen to bring salvation to the world is by working through people.

20:58.070 --> 21:01.313
Blaze Pascal called this the dignity of causality.

21:02.574 --> 21:08.680
That God bestows upon us the honor of being part of something way bigger than ourselves.

21:09.501 --> 21:16.687
He entrusts us with his precious gospel and we're the ones that get to bring it to the world.

21:17.869 --> 21:19.410
It's a huge responsibility

21:20.226 --> 21:22.188
but it's an amazing opportunity.

21:23.629 --> 21:30.536
Because pretty much every person who knows Jesus knows him because of someone else, right?

21:31.116 --> 21:49.874
Like there are rare exceptions, but I'm guessing the reason you're in this room today is because someone in your life, a parent, a friend, a relative, a youth leader, someone loved you enough to share Jesus with you and changed your life forever.

21:51.586 --> 22:01.382
This is how God, in his grace and kindness, has chosen to disseminate his gospel to the world through people like you and I.

22:02.523 --> 22:07.030
Which is why Paul asks, how can anyone call the name of the Lord if they don't believe in him?

22:07.411 --> 22:09.775
And how can they believe in him if they haven't heard about him?

22:10.155 --> 22:13.641
And how can they hear about him without someone telling them?

22:18.288 --> 22:19.410
So let me ask you.

22:22.082 --> 22:28.870
When was the last time you shared with someone what Jesus means to you?

22:31.413 --> 22:37.741
When was the last time you described the difference that Christ has made in your life?

22:40.524 --> 22:47.573
When was the last time you explained to a friend why you have the hope that you do?

22:50.537 --> 22:51.698
And if it's been a while,

22:53.410 --> 23:03.566
that I have to ask you, like Paul, how will the people in your life ever hear the gospel if you won't tell them?

23:03.586 --> 23:08.454
And how will they ever believe the good news if you won't share it with them?

23:10.537 --> 23:16.306
And how will your friends ever meet Jesus if you won't introduce them?

23:20.674 --> 23:26.140
That's how big of a role God has called you to play in his story of redemption.

23:27.742 --> 23:36.931
And I'm convinced that for every single one of us in this room, there is at least one person who is waiting for us to share the good news with them.

23:38.433 --> 23:46.922
There's at least one person in your life who you are uniquely designed and perfectly situated to reach in a way that no one else can.

23:47.923 --> 23:50.546
That's the dignity of causality.

23:51.266 --> 23:59.655
There are people you know who Jesus wants to save and he's waiting for you to tell them about him.

24:02.278 --> 24:08.185
Now, for some of you that pumps you up and you're ready to go hit the streets, for others of us, that freaks us out.

24:09.406 --> 24:11.128
So let's get practical for a moment.

24:11.829 --> 24:15.894
What does evangelism actually look like for ordinary Christians like us?

24:16.815 --> 24:19.698
What does this look like in real life?

24:21.090 --> 24:26.055
Tim Keller used to say that the highest form of evangelism is friendship.

24:27.457 --> 24:30.200
He said, there's no such thing as friendship evangelism.

24:31.041 --> 24:31.842
There's friendship.

24:33.303 --> 24:42.713
And if you're friends with someone, as long as you don't intentionally hide the fact that you're a Christian from them, it will come up eventually, right?

24:43.374 --> 24:44.415
This is what friends do.

24:45.016 --> 24:46.117
They share their lives.

24:46.197 --> 24:50.642
They tell their stories, including their spiritual beliefs.

24:51.458 --> 24:59.726
So if you've been friends with somebody for like five years and they still have no idea you're a Christian, you're not a bad evangelist.

24:59.746 --> 25:00.587
You're a bad friend.

25:02.149 --> 25:03.130
That's just kind of weird.

25:03.890 --> 25:05.912
It's like, oh, we've known each other for 10 years.

25:06.032 --> 25:07.094
I didn't know you were married.

25:07.614 --> 25:08.715
Like, that's strange.

25:08.875 --> 25:10.076
I thought we were friends.

25:13.440 --> 25:18.124
So you don't need to force your beliefs or cram anything down anybody's throat.

25:18.145 --> 25:19.666
That's not what we're talking about.

25:20.674 --> 25:23.939
We're just talking about being your honest, authentic self.

25:24.620 --> 25:32.592
And as you and your friends get to know each other, the Holy Spirit will give you plenty of opportunities to talk about Jesus and what he means to you.

25:33.393 --> 25:36.518
That's what I've found in my life over and over again.

25:36.558 --> 25:38.541
So forget friendship evangelism.

25:39.463 --> 25:41.045
Let's just be good friends.

25:42.187 --> 25:44.490
Jesus himself was called a friend of sinners.

25:44.550 --> 25:46.994
And I think that's a good goal for all of us.

25:47.714 --> 25:49.476
Okay, so we can all do that.

25:49.816 --> 25:52.399
We're all called to the work of evangelism.

25:54.501 --> 25:59.587
But some are called to be evangelists, and that's the last word I wanna talk about.

26:00.408 --> 26:04.012
When you hear the word evangelist, I wonder what comes to your mind.

26:04.652 --> 26:07.055
I'm guessing for a lot of us, it's something like this.

26:11.820 --> 26:17.426
Health and wealth, prosperity preachers with private jets and bad hair,

26:17.634 --> 26:21.878
who are taking advantage of vulnerable people who are looking for a miracle.

26:22.779 --> 26:32.388
And even though almost all of these televangelists get caught up in some kind of scandal, somehow you can still find them on TV pretty much 24-7.

26:33.048 --> 26:37.473
These guys have given evangelists a bad name.

26:37.513 --> 26:42.617
But if you think this is what evangelists look like, I've actually got news for you.

26:42.657 --> 26:47.602
Did you know we have some real live evangelists here at Antioch?

26:48.130 --> 26:51.074
And I don't just mean in the sense that we're all called to evangelize.

26:51.455 --> 26:58.886
We've got a handful of folks who are dedicating their lives to sharing the gospel of Jesus here in Bend.

26:59.968 --> 27:03.173
And they don't look like this, they actually look like this.

27:06.218 --> 27:10.744
Justin Scott, Skyler Locklin, Emily and Kyle Cardinal.

27:11.486 --> 27:17.074
These are some of our local young life leaders who happen to be part of our church family here.

27:17.666 --> 27:21.792
Justin is the Young Life Area Director for all of Central Oregon.

27:22.373 --> 27:25.898
He leads the high school clubs at Bend High and at Caldera.

27:26.339 --> 27:31.086
Skyler oversees the team and leads the club at Mountain View High, Go Cougs.

27:31.106 --> 27:34.010
And Kyle and Emily also serve as Mountain View volunteers.

27:35.312 --> 27:40.660
Kyle and Emily, by the way, definitely win this year's award for best photo in the church directory.

27:42.002 --> 27:44.986
And I know I've said these guys don't look like you're typical evangelists.

27:45.567 --> 27:47.410
Go back to the first picture real quick.

27:48.418 --> 27:51.001
Okay, no, go back to the other one.

27:51.021 --> 27:52.482
I don't know.

27:52.502 --> 27:57.107
There's definitely some similarities, right?

27:57.127 --> 27:58.308
I'm not sure what that is.

27:58.909 --> 28:01.692
But these guys are real evangelists.

28:01.812 --> 28:04.055
And as young life leaders, here's what they do.

28:04.095 --> 28:14.866
They spend their lives going to where middle schoolers and high schoolers in our city are and building real relationships with them and introducing them to the real Jesus.

28:15.042 --> 28:20.188
This is what Young Life has been doing since the 1940s, all around the world.

28:20.669 --> 28:25.735
So by show hands, how many of you have been involved or impacted by Young Life in one way or another?

28:26.316 --> 28:28.238
Yeah, it's amazing.

28:28.739 --> 28:31.682
Millions of kids have met Jesus through Young Life.

28:31.742 --> 28:37.850
Jen and I got to be at the Young Life banquet a few days ago, and it was packed from people all over Central Oregon.

28:38.270 --> 28:44.658
If you go out into a hall and look on our wall of ministry partners, you'll see Young Life is one of the local ministries

28:44.770 --> 28:47.296
that we love to support and work with.

28:47.397 --> 28:52.810
And in fact, last week, they used our building here to throw their citywide Halloween party for high schoolers.

28:53.532 --> 28:57.562
And so I just want to shout out to our resident evangelists.

28:58.023 --> 29:00.690
I don't, are any of you guys here this morning?

29:01.090 --> 29:02.712
They're usually second service.

29:02.752 --> 29:14.688
So we do love them and we are so proud of them and so thankful for the difference that they're making in our city, in our churches, in our schools, in our families, including my own.

29:15.349 --> 29:27.345
So to sum it all up, the mission of Christ's church has always had two sides, social justice and evangelism.

29:28.647 --> 29:30.930
But they aren't two disconnected things.

29:32.258 --> 29:49.440
They're two sides of the same coin, showing and telling the gospel, demonstrating and declaring the good news, meeting physical and spiritual needs, word and deed, audio and video.

29:50.782 --> 29:55.648
And Antioch has a reputation for being a church that cares about justice.

29:56.850 --> 29:57.931
And I love that about us.

29:58.872 --> 30:00.274
I hope it never changes.

30:01.602 --> 30:03.545
Because we're gonna keep chasing justice.

30:04.607 --> 30:18.008
We're gonna keep feeding the hungry and serving the poor and standing with the oppressed and welcoming the stranger and confronting racism and caring for creation and disarming weapons and waging peace wherever we can.

30:18.408 --> 30:20.551
We will never stop pursuing justice.

30:23.376 --> 30:29.906
But let's also make sure that we aren't ashamed to preach what we practice.

30:31.746 --> 30:39.916
Let's make sure that we love our neighbors enough to share with them the hope that we found in Christ.

30:41.819 --> 30:42.680
The video works.

30:43.761 --> 30:45.744
Let's make sure the audio is not on mute.

30:47.626 --> 30:50.690
Of course, this isn't a new or unique position to Antioch.

30:51.972 --> 30:55.336
This is what faithfulness to the whole gospel has always looked like.

30:55.917 --> 31:00.242
And I'll close with a few lines from a book called The Kingdom of God

31:00.354 --> 31:03.778
which was written by a Presbyterian biblical scholar in 1953.

31:06.662 --> 31:21.481
We can't preach the ethics of Jesus and leave behind his mission in personhood, nor can we urge people to saving faith in Christ, but not confront the systemic issues and demands of righteousness of the kingdom.

31:22.623 --> 31:28.210
We do not have two gospels, social and personal, we have one gospel.

31:28.674 --> 31:32.211
the gospel of the kingdom of God, and it is both.

31:33.075 --> 31:36.290
We have simply nothing else to preach.

31:37.736 --> 31:38.098
Amen.

